        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Sydenham | Belfast</placeName>
                    <date>24 March | 1878</date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir,</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
                    <p>Illness has delayed my reply.<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
                    <p>Sales of varieties of 1875 have reduced the amount needed to £50 on first May and £50 on first August next.</p>
                    <p>If however Mr Farrer and Mr Caird, to whom I am deeply indebted, desire it, I will undertake to utilize another £100 payable in July and returnable as well as the first Hundred next spring—<ref target="#foot.f2"/> I only want to keep my word not to spend more money on this matter at present.</p>
                    <p>I beg leave to return herewith your most highly valued check in order that the payments may be re-arranged.</p>
<p>With profound respect I am my dear Sir | faithfully yours | James Torbitt</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            
            </div>
            
            
            <div type="footnotes">
                <note xml:id="foot.f1">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11436.xml">letter to James Torbitt, 21 March [1878]</ref>.</note>
                <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD had sent a cheque for £100 to enable Torbitt to continue his potato experiments for another season if a government grant could not be obtained (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11399.xml">letter to James Torbitt, 4 March 1878</ref>). See also <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11435.xml">letter from T. H. Farrer, 20 March 1878</ref>, and <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11437.xml">letter from James Caird, 21 March 1878</ref>.</note>
